properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An extended period of freezing rain is expected. Locations: Deer Lake - Humber Valley as well as communities south of Green Bay. Time span: continuing until noon today. Remarks: Freezing rain will slowly transition over to flurries by midday today. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2020-01-27T17:59:06-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-01-27T08:43:06-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3931165911.2020
Area: Deer Lake - Humber Valley, Green Bay - White Bay
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall expected. Total rainfall: 20 to 30 mm. Locations: Connaigre and Burin Peninsulas. Time span: continuing until early this afternoon. Remarks: The rainfall will be accompanied by temperatures a few degrees above zero. Areas with deep existing snow pack will be vulnerable to snowmelt and water runoff, with localized flooding possible. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Freezing Drizzle Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A weak flow from the Gulf of St Lawrence is producing conditions favourable for the development of freezing drizzle early this morning. ### Freezing drizzle can produce thin, hard-to-detect layers of ice. Freezing drizzle advisories are issued when drizzle falling in sub-zero temperatures is expected to freeze on contact, and over time create icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain and rain expected. Rainfall amounts: 5 mm. Locations: central and northeastern Newfoundland. Timespan: overnight tonight to Monday afternoon. Remarks: Precipitation will begin as freezing rain overnight tonight in central and early Monday morning in the northeast. The freezing rain has the potential to persist for several hours before transitioning to rain by late Monday morning. The rain is expected to taper off late Monday afternoon. The rainfall will be accompanied by above zero temperatures over central and northeastern Newfoundland. Areas with deep existing snow pack will be vulnerable to snowmelt and water runoff, with localized flooding possible. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Areas of dense fog are developing throughout southern Saskatchewan. This fog will become more widespread overnight especially in southwestern Saskatchewan. There will be local pockets of freezing drizzle tonight and Monday morning. The fog will lift in most areas Monday morning. The fog may persist into Monday afternoon in some localities towards the Alberta border. Fog may also redevelop Monday night. ### Fog advisories are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Maximum wind gusts: northeasterly 80 km/h. Locations: the Great Northern Peninsula. Time span: this afternoon until Tuesday morning. Remarks: Fresh snowfall will combine with strengthening northeasterly winds to give poor visibility in blowing snow. Conditions are expected to improve by Tuesday morning as the winds begin to ease. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures well into the minus thirties with light winds will bring periods of extreme wind chills around -50 today and tonight. These extreme wind chills will moderate slightly for Tuesday. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and persistent visibility near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong pressure gradient over the Northwest Territories, combined with lower pressure over the Yukon, is generating strong winds through the Richardson Mountains. Easterly winds of 100 km/h with gusts to 110 at Rock River is generating blowing snow with near zero visibility near the Richardson Mountains this evening, Blizzard conditions are expected to end overnight as the winds ease. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
